The [1992 United States presidential election in New Jersey](/1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_New_Jersey) unfolded on November 3, 1992, as an integral part of the broader [1992 United States presidential election](/1992_United_States_presidential_election). Voters across the state were tasked with selecting 15 representatives, known as electors, to the [Electoral College](/United_States_Electoral_College), who would then formally cast their votes for the nation's [president](/President_of_the_United_States) and [vice president](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States).

In a contest that signaled a national shift, [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) ultimately cast its lot with [Governor](/List_of_governors_of_Arkansas) [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton), the [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) nominee from [Arkansas](/Arkansas). Clinton secured 42.95% of the popular vote, narrowly besting the incumbent President [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), a [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) from [Texas](/Texas), who received 40.58%. This represented a rather slender 2.37% margin of victory for Clinton, a difference that, while small, proved decisive. The political landscape was further complicated by the significant presence of independent businessman [Ross Perot](/Ross_Perot), also hailing from [Texas](/Texas), who, running as an [Independent](/Independent_politician), managed to capture a notable 15.61% of the popular vote. This three-way race undoubtedly reshaped the dynamics in many states, including New Jersey, siphoning votes from both major parties. Nationally, Clinton mirrored his New Jersey success, ultimately winning the presidential election and unseating President Bush. [2]

For decades leading up to this election, [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) had been firmly entrenched in the category of a Republican-leaning [swing state](/Swing_state). Its electoral behavior often wavered, but with a discernible tilt towards the Republican Party in presidential contests. Clinton's victory in 1992 thus marked a significant turning point, representing the first instance a [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) candidate had carried the state since [Lyndon Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson)'s overwhelming landslide [win in 1964](/1964_United_States_presidential_election_in_New_Jersey). Johnson's victory, coming amidst a national Democratic wave and the aftermath of President Kennedy's assassination, was an anomaly in the state's post-World War II Republican trend, making Clinton's 1992 win even more noteworthy. Indeed, this particular election holds the distinction of being the last time [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) would vote to the right of its historically bellwether neighbor, [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania), highlighting a diverging political trajectory that would become more pronounced in subsequent years. [3]

This outcome marked only the third occasion since the conclusion of [World War II](/World_War_II) that [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) had delivered its electoral votes to a [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) presidential candidate. Following this election, despite the incredibly slim margin recorded in 1992, the state would embark on a consistent pattern of supporting Democratic presidential nominees, typically by margins exceeding 10 points. The only notable exceptions to this developing trend occurred in [2004](/2004_United_States_presidential_election_in_New_Jersey), when [John Kerry](/John_Kerry)'s margin of victory in New Jersey was just under 7 points, and more recently in [2024](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_New_Jersey), where [Kamala Harris](/Kamala_Harris)'s lead was just under 6 points. These exceptions, however, merely serve to underscore the broader shift of New Jersey from a swing state to a reliably blue stronghold over the decades.

The electoral results of 1992 also hold several distinctions that, as of 2024, represent the last of their kind. This was the final presidential election cycle in which [Bergen County](/Bergen_County,_New_Jersey), a densely populated and historically competitive suburban area, voted Republican. Similarly, [Passaic County](/Passaic_County,_New_Jersey) would not return a Republican vote in a presidential race again until the [2024 election](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_New_Jersey). Furthermore, 1992 was the last presidential election until 2024 where the Republican candidate managed to secure a majority of the state's counties, indicating a geographic shift in party dominance. It was also the last time the electoral preferences of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) aligned to the right of the country as a whole, a statistic that underscores its broader political evolution. Ultimately, this election marked the final period where New Jersey was genuinely considered a [swing state](/Swing_state) in the traditional sense, a status it would not reclaim until the heated [2024 United States Presidential Election](/2024_United_States_presidential_election). [4]

