The county results reveal a stark geographic divide. Urban and inner-suburban counties like [Essex](/Essex_County,_New_Jersey), [Hudson](/Hudson_County,_New_Jersey), [Camden](/Camden_County,_New_Jersey), and [Mercer](/Mercer_County,_New_Jersey) delivered strong majorities for [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton), reflecting the Democratic Party's growing strength in metropolitan areas. For instance, [Essex County](/Essex_County,_New_Jersey) gave Clinton a commanding 57.12% of its votes, highlighting its status as a Democratic bastion even then. Conversely, traditionally Republican strongholds in the more affluent northern and western parts of the state, such as [Morris](/Morris_County,_New_Jersey), [Sussex](/Sussex_County,_New_Jersey), [Hunterdon](/Hunterdon_County,_New_Jersey), and [Somerset](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) counties, remained steadfastly loyal to [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), with Bush securing over 50% in [Morris](/Morris_County,_New_Jersey) and [Sussex](/Sussex_County,_New_Jersey) counties. The coastal [Ocean County](/Ocean_County,_New_Jersey) also leaned heavily Republican.

The fact that the Republican candidate, [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), managed to win a majority of the state's counties in 1992, despite losing the popular vote statewide, is a testament to the persistent rural and suburban conservative base that existed at the time. This demographic pattern, where a significant number of counties could vote Republican while the state as a whole leaned Democratic, would become increasingly rare in subsequent presidential elections, further cementing 1992 as a critical inflection point in New Jersey's political alignment. The relatively strong showing of [Ross Perot](/Ross_Perot) across many counties, particularly in areas like [Gloucester](/Gloucester_County,_New_Jersey) and [Warren](/Warren_County,_New_Jersey) where he exceeded 23% of the vote, also demonstrates the widespread dissatisfaction with both major parties, subtly influencing the final margins.

## Results by congressional district

[Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton) demonstrated his ability to appeal across various regions of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), successfully carrying 8 of the state's 13 congressional districts. Notably, one of these victories occurred in a district that was at the time represented by a [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) incumbent, underscoring the broader electoral shift taking place in 1992. This ability to break through Republican-held territories at the district level provided a clear indication of the Democratic Party's resurgent strength in the state. [6]

