The distribution of votes by congressional district further illustrates the localized political dynamics within [New Jersey](/New_Jersey). Districts like the 10th, encompassing parts of [Essex](/Essex_County,_New_Jersey) and [Union](/Union_County,_New_Jersey) counties, showed an overwhelming preference for [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton), with a staggering 72.1% of the vote. This is indicative of a strong urban and minority vote base, which traditionally leans Democratic. In contrast, districts such as the 5th and 11th, covering more affluent and historically conservative suburban and rural areas, heavily favored [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), with Bush securing over 49% and 51% respectively. These districts, often characterized by higher income levels and a more homogeneous demographic, remained bastions of Republican support.

The presence of [Ross Perot](/Ross_Perot)'s vote share, which often hovered between 15% and 20% in many districts, suggests that his appeal was broad, drawing support from voters who might otherwise have split between the two major parties. His performance in districts like the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd, where he garnered nearly a fifth of the vote, indicates a significant level of voter dissatisfaction that transcended traditional party lines. This nuanced breakdown by district highlights how New Jersey, despite its statewide lean, was a mosaic of varying political sentiments, a characteristic that makes it endlessly fascinating, or perhaps, just endlessly complicated.

